07603nam a22010455i 9789048550203DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20192019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485502037 a10.1515/97890485502032doi  a(DE-B1597)542040  a(OCoLC)1143795719  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aH 7aPOL0700002bisacsh00aBorder Deaths :bCauses, Dynamics and Consequences of Migration-related Mortality /ced. by Tamara Last, Paolo Cuttitta. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (174 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface: The Increasing Focus on Border Deaths -- tIntroduction: A State-of-the-Art Exposition on Border Deaths -- t1. Various Actors: The Border Death Regime -- t2. Mortality and Border Deaths Data -- t3. Representations of Border Deaths and the Making and Unmaking of Borders -- t4. Engaging Bodies as Matters of Care -- t5. Mourning Missing Migrants -- t6. Enforced Disappearances and Border Deaths Along the Migrant Trail -- t7. Understanding the Causes of Border Deaths -- t8. Moving forward Afterword: From the Iron Curtain to Lampedusa -- tAfterword: From the Iron Curtain to Lampedusa -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aBorder deaths are a result of dynamics involving diverse actors, and can be interpreted and represented in various ways. Critical voices from civil society (including academia) hold states responsible for making safe journeys impossible for large parts of the world population. Meanwhile, policy-makers argue that border deaths demonstrate the need for restrictive border policies. Statistics are widely (mis)used to support different readings of border deaths. However, the way data is collected, analysed, and disseminated remains largely unquestioned. Similarly, little is known about how bodies are treated, and about the different ways in which the dead - also including the missing and the unidentified - are mourned by familiars and strangers. New concepts and perspectives contribute to highlighting the political nature of border deaths and finding ways to move forward. The chapters of this collection, co-authored by researchers and practitioners, provide the first interdisciplinary overview of this contested field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aConflict and Peace. 4aContemporary Society. 4aInternational Relations. 4aLaw. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh  aBorders.  aDeaths.  aIrregular migration.  aMigrant mortality.  aMigration policy.1 aBasilien-Gainche, Marie-Laure, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuttitta, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuttitta, Paolo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDearden, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDijstelbloem, Huub, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDistretti, Emilio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGombeer, Kristof, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorsti, Karina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHäberlein, Jana, econtributor